<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is found in the epipelagic zone (0-200 m depth) of the Pacific and Indian Oceans (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
) and the Tosa Bay in Japan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, it was found in the epipelagic zone (0-100 m depth) of the Korea Strait and northern East China Sea (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
: stations KS09 and nECS06).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Beraneck" baseAuthorityYear="1895" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Zonosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zonosagitta bedoti" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="bedoti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Zonosagitta bedoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is used as an indicator species in the front area where warm and cold water meet (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). The temperature range in the sampling location in this study was between 14.62 and 15.01 °C and the salinity range was 33.67-33.81 psu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Beraneck" baseAuthorityYear="1895" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Zonosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zonosagitta bedoti" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="bedoti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Zonosagitta bedoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Z." lsidName="Z. nagae" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="nagae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Z. nagae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in morphology at the immature stage. However, because adult 
<taxonomicName genus="Z." lsidName="Z. nagae" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="nagae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Z. nagae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are relatively larger, immature 
<taxonomicName genus="Z." lsidName="Z. nagae" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="nagae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Z. nagae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be misidentified as 
<taxonomicName genus="Z." lsidName="Z. bedoti" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="bedoti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Z. bedoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Adults of both species can be distinguished from each other by the shape of seminal vesicles and eye pigments. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alvarino" baseAuthorityYear="1967" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Zonosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zonosagitta nagae" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="nagae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Zonosagitta nagae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“E”">&quot;E&quot;</normalizedToken>
-shaped eye pigment, while 
<taxonomicName genus="Z." lsidName="Z. bedoti" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="bedoti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Z. bedoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a star-shaped eye pigment. The spot pattern on the body surface found through CBE staining is as follows: irregular spot pattern which continued from the head to the ventral ganglion and six spots along the outside of the body were symmetrical around the tail.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
